# Testing the Integration

You can manually trigger an alarm state change using the AWS CLI.

```
aws cloudwatch set-alarm-state \
--alarm-name EC2-CPU-High \
--state-value ALARM \
--state-reason "Manual test"
```

This will trigger the workflow:

```
CloudWatch Alarm
    ↓
EventBridge Rule
    ↓
Lambda Function
    ↓
DevOps Agent Webhook
```

---

# Example Incident Payload

Example payload sent to the DevOps Agent webhook.

```json
{
  "eventType": "incident",
  "incidentId": "cw-EC2-CPU-High-1700000000000",
  "action": "created",
  "priority": "CRITICAL",
  "title": "ALARM: EC2-CPU-High",
  "description": "Threshold Crossed",
  "timestamp": "2026-03-04T01:00:00Z",
  "service": "CloudWatch",
  "data": {
    "metadata": {
      "region": "us-east-1",
      "environment": "prod",
      "accountId": "373099676716"
    },
    "tags": {
      "auto_investigate": "true",
      "env": "prod"
    },
    "cloudwatch": {
      "alarmName": "EC2-CPU-High",
      "state": "ALARM",
      "threshold": 80,
      "metric": "CPUUtilization"
    }
  }
}
```

---

# Lambda Permissions

The Lambda function requires the following permissions:

```
cloudwatch:DescribeAlarms
cloudwatch:ListTagsForResource
cloudwatch:GetMetricStatistics
secretsmanager:GetSecretValue
sts:GetCallerIdentity
```

These permissions are included in the CloudFormation template.

